Sr. worthy freind I have recd. yd of 27: past., you had recd. our bale of kersies
& sold 6 p I hope you will finde sale for the rest, as also for what Elce you
bring to markett for I am told that you have a considerable trade & vere
quick demand, so I hope the proffitt will in corridge the continumey
for here I finde itt growes from badd toworse & now I can tell
12 whare house in this towne where in the bine of smoth a vale thare
vas butt 3 & when the spanish g round was so large so leave you to
considder how wee are mr. konthath been. here 4 dayes butt I have spoten
tohi in butt onss & made not attall of him, no more then a stranger
with few words on the exs & no more of the rest I finde by otbeer
that he was extramely I alovs yett tis his old honour, prtend to continew
a little nt with t12 & a 8 &non Elce for one m. potter dothvere
well in the north cloathes for Ay much better then till: the goods
I had from pichering & Rolinson are hardely vendable, some already
lost there press sence the death of demont I begoun his farrique
of modecolleurs and whit goods to be dyed black or soablett, the Roosendnes
Doth the some, and am told he hath a freind att lille which sells als what
he prepares for he doth leave off trade here where fore thought good to
desire you to informe how that traade goeths, for I could fournish
you with such cloth aswell as her I haveing the best warch peopee
if I can meet a small remise shall send itt, & ought I am extreamly scary
a 3 gber 168
egt yd answer & remaine
London Abram Vivian
the
Sr. I have before mee boath yd of 15 & 18 past I hope you shall endeavour
that my order for the 50 or 60 bayes more shall be compleatend as well
as the rest, for I am almost out off all my bayes here & neglect not
butt that they some with vinder att least & seengtis necessary that
wee make use of mr. Shipping becauused of the reason
a Aleudged lest itt be se & recommand hereustley to take
notice of each pack itts contents marckes & o that so when I open amy
I know what is what: tis good that they beginne to know their fautt
of last bayes which in deed have been butt 50s in all for struted
itt onelij to my self the examination of them & did depend upon
no boddj Elve. I have the bill of loading for 3 bayes aboard smith I hope
the bayes shall yett come with him, if not with pindar at least
wath the rest of the in ordered goods I could have wished smith has had
a bale more my thanckes for the paines you took in getting my 2
bills accepted I do wonder now you should draw so Â£200: againe, realy
itt is be yondexspectation the more because I have don all I could do
in my power to prevent drawing & to suply you with the needfull
& after that to Draw Â£65d: in 5 weekes is un reasonable
I have amuch & farr greater concerne with m. Henry maynard
in goods from London, yett he drewnoke one houndred pourd
all this yeare, I confess I was contented that you might draw
on mee up on apinche butt not affer this rate principally where
I do all I can on my side to suplt you with the needfull if you
ximin mj acctt. you will finde itt so, if you examm yd yon
must needs finde that the returnes are pretty well if you compare
the voage to antwarp with the returnes butt to give you more
content shall draw out all the acctt. of sale of every month sence
xb. last & send you Ilove to please my freinds butt a draw ng toade ran
not abide, I have well rec. the peece of lace, andis almost finithed
which as soone as don shall be seat you with the rest to compbat
one packett haveing above ready & hope yett to dispatch itt this
week itt shall be off rossen onely & she that provided the packett N.16: laces
are verey cleay now & never where they cheaper, so you may vere well
exspect a groat penny worth assorted to yd content which I remaide
London Henri Maijnard

Sr. I wrott to you the 30: past. come what in laste, whoever referre you
to the same, concerning a bale of redds to be assorted from Â£8:10 to Â£15:-
ap: &2 or 3 anvoras in all 12 peeces, which neglect not to dispatch as
soone as possible, butt where as you are use to hang out one had with the
number & leiight of boath Â½ p. so besides that, desire that on the end
of each halfe red be alead of all hangh out as formerly, so that when
wee sell them either by whole or halves I can finde out the leinght
I have sold all our frises, so desire you to send mee an other bale to containe
the same assortment of the last & that the sooner the better be causee
I must putt them off before winter: inclade orsendin some pack or other
2 or 3 paire of white women cotton hose for my wifer of the least sort
a little fort, which commission, though itt be trouble some, yett pros
considder tis for a woman: John simons is not as yett arrived intrim
by the by a word of John kent which hath been here 4 dayes: I have spoke
to him butt ones up on the ex in full comp. butt as I understand from
other hand hath ablad & pratt lett so much that he deserved
J alusye doth exceed above all his honours amonghst other he told,
that I remitted him Â£2000: st to be imployed in northren goods, butt that
he refused my commissions & so know not how many storres, nox en him
I never wrott Johnn sence 1678:- when Ileft him butt I find tis John
kentstill I have no more to inlarge butt that I am with kinde salute
London Henry Coblier
@ 3 gber 1688

Sr. I have before mee yd of 12: past. & rec. one from ud soam of 15 ditto
with the letters of 18, you have don mee preiudice & discredit in not sending
invoyce, or prijses att least of the cottons for I have bought Esle were
I have opened them all yeasterday, & finde they are well bought so shall yett
endeavour to sell y well you could easely please mee could you pass without
drawing, for I am ready to warck all the dayes of my life, and that with
as much care & Exttetness as I can, to gett my liuing (with gods blessing) & a
penny or twoo more to leave my children though I confess the oldmon takes
that o heard I have accepted yd bill for Â£67:10â3: & button hath accepted yd of
Â£50:- herreynce told mee yeasterday that wee gott a further sentence against
T.H. I hape he will not appell itt to Brussells, that wee shall be able to do with
itt time shall learne whilst I rest n
Aust John Button
